definition.value: A macromolecule composed of repeating 1-(dodecylcarbamoyl)ethylene units.
A macromolecule containing sulfur-sulfur linkages in the backbone.
The fatty amide resulting from the formal condensation of oleic acid and aniline.
A fatty amide conjugate of linoleic acid and aniline.
A macromolecule composed of repeating (2-methoxy-5-sulfo-1,4-phenylene)imino units.
A macromolecule composed of repeating (2Z)-2-chlorobut-2-ene-1,4-diyl units.
A polymer composed of repeating 1,1-dimethylethylene units.
A 2,4-dichloro-1,3,5-triazine with a multi-substituted napthalen-1-ylamino substituent at the 6-position.
A sulfonamide consisting of pyrimidine having a methoxy substituent at the 5-position and a 4-aminobenzenesulfonamido group at the 2-position.
An aminoxyl (nitroxide) free radical dipalmitoyl glycerophosphoethanolamine derivative used as a hapten in immunological investigations.
A sulfone compound having two S-vinyl substituents.
An  aporphine alkaloid that is (S)-1,2,9,10-tetrahydroxy-6-methyl-5,6,6a,7-tetrahydro-4H-dibenzo[de,g]quinoline in which the four phenolic hydrogens have been replaced by methyl groups.
An azo compound having a ({[(2-sulfonatooxy)ethyl]sulfonyl}phenyl)diazenyl moiety attached at position 2 of a multi-substituted naphthalene.
A bis(azo) compound with two aryldiazenyl moieties placed at positions 2 and 7 of a multi-substituted naphthalene.
An isocyanate comprising a benzene core with isocyanato and methyl substituents para to each other.
The organosulfonate oxoanion that is the dianionic form of the azo dye remazole orange-3R.
The organosulfonate oxoanion that is the tetraanionic form of the azo dye remazole black-GR.
A macromolecule composed of repeating methyl methacrylate units in which some of the hydrogen atoms have been replaced by deuterium atoms.
A macromolecule composed of repeating fully deuterated methyl methacrylate units.
A macromolecule composed of repeating methyl methacrylate units in which the five hydrogen atoms on the methacrylate moiety have been replaced by deuterium atoms.
A macromolecule composed of repeating methyl methacrylate units in which three of the hydrogen atoms on the methacrylate moiety have been replaced by deuterium atoms.
An L-tyrosine derivative having an N(alpha)-acetyl substituent and a 4-arsonophenyldiazenyl group at the 3-position of the benzene ring.
A dolichyl diphosphooligosaccharide compound consisting of a branched pentasaccharide attached to the dolichyl chain via a diphosphate linkage.
A 1,3-oxazolone derivative having a nitrophenyl substituent at the 2-position, an ethoxymethylene group at the 4-position, and an oxo group at the 5-position.
A 1,2,4-triazine compound having oxo-substituents at the 3- and 5-positions.

An EC 1.1.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-OH group, NAD(+) or NADP(+) acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of IMP dehydrogenase (EC 1.1.1.205), so blocking de novo biosynthesis of purine nucleotides.
A tripeptide consisting of AcTyrGlyGly with a (4-arsonophenyl)diazenyl group at the 3-position on the tyrosine phenyl ring.
A tripeptide consisting of AcTyrGlyGlyNHNHBoc with a (4-arsonophenyl)diazenyl group at the 3-position on the tyrosine phenyl ring.
The mesylate salt of gemifloxacin.
The D-(-)-tartrate salt of vinorelbine.
A fatty amide conjugate of alpha-linolenic acid and aniline.
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxylic acid group to the amino group of L-aspartic acid 4-semialdehyde.
A carboxylic ester that is a modified acyl glycerol with oleyl and linoleyl entities at C-1 and C-2, respectively, and an aniline moiety at C-3.
A triglyceride formed by esterification of the three hydroxy groups of glycerol with oleic acid. Triolein is one of the two components of Lorenzo's oil.
A  carboxylic ester that is a modified acyl glycerol with oleoyl and linolenoyl entities at C-1 and C-2, respectively, and an aniline moiety at C-3.
A  carboxylic ester that is a modified acyl glycerol with linolenyl and linoleyl entities at C-1 and C-2, respectively; and an anilino moiety at C-3.
An entity which inhibits the activity of HIV-1 reverse transcriptase.
The methanesulfonate trihydrate salt of ziprasidone.
A glycol that is a derivative of glycerol in which one of the hydroxy groups is replaced by an anilino group.
A triglyceride formed by esterification of the three hydroxy groups of glycerol with elaidic acid.

The (5S)- (active) enantiomer of zopiclone. Unlike almost all other hypnotic sedatives, which are approved only for the relief of short-term (6-8 weeks) insomnia, eszopiclone is approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for long-term use.
A diblock copolymer composed of adjacent blocks of poly(ethylene glycol) and poly(glycerol 1-O-monomethacrylate).
The (5R)-enantiomer of zopiclone.
A piperidine compound having a (2-thienyl)ethyl substituent at the 1-position, a methyl group at the 3-position and an N-phenylpropanamido group at the 4-position.
The (R)-enantiomer of 3-methylthiofentanyl.
The (S)-enantiomer of 3-methylthiofentanyl.
